Note:
==============================================================================
CMYK - Subtractive Print Color Model
==============================================================================

CMYK represents the four-ink subtractive colour model used by every
offset printing press, ink-jet plotter, and process-colour digital
press. The four channels are:
    C : cyan ink density 0..1
    M : magenta ink density 0..1
    Y : yellow ink density 0..1
    K : key (black) ink density 0..1

The conversions between CMYK and RGB are inherently device-dependent
because real inks behave non-linearly and depend on substrate, ink
loading, and dot gain. The "naive" conversion in this module is the
simple subtractive transform that ignores ICC profile work:

    From RGB to CMYK:
        K = 1 - max(R, G, B)
        if K = 1: C = M = Y = 0
        else:
            C = (1 - R - K) / (1 - K)
            M = (1 - G - K) / (1 - K)
            Y = (1 - B - K) / (1 - K)

    From CMYK to RGB:
        R = (1 - C) * (1 - K)
        G = (1 - M) * (1 - K)
        B = (1 - Y) * (1 - K)

For production printing, callers must apply an ICC profile (e.g.,
GRACoL, Fogra51, JapanColor) which this module does NOT implement.
ICC profile evaluation belongs in a higher-level color management
service that consumes the linear-CMYK output produced here.

The total ink coverage (TIC, also called TAC for Total Area Coverage)
predicate cmyk_total_ink_coverage is provided for press constraint
checking; print houses commonly limit TIC to 240-320% to avoid ink
saturation and drying issues.

References:
  - SWOP (Specifications for Web Offset Publications)
  - GRACoL (General Requirements for Applications in Commercial Offset
    Lithography)
  - ISO 12647-2:2013 (Graphic technology - Process control)
  - ISO 15076-1:2010 (Image technology colour management - ICC
    profile format)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "CMYK":
    c as Float
    m as Float
    y as Float
    k as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOCAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "clamp01" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Saturate a Float to [0, 1]. Used by every CMYK constructor and
    conversion to enforce the channel invariant.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares against literal endpoints.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ucomisd + two cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    If v is greater than 1.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Process called "max3" takes a as Float, b as Float, c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Pointwise maximum of three Floats used by the RGB -> K extraction
    formula.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two sequential compares with predicated update.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares + two cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let m be a
    If b is greater than m:
        Set m to b
    End If
    If c is greater than m:
        Set m to c
    End If
    Return m
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "cmyk_create" takes c as Float, m as Float, y as Float, k as Float returns CMYK:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a CMYK with each ink channel clamped to [0, 1]. The total
    ink coverage check is intentionally NOT performed at construction
    time; callers that need TIC enforcement must call
    cmyk_total_ink_coverage explicitly.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per-channel clamp01.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four ucomisd + four cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type CMYK
    Set out.c to clamp01(c)
    Set out.m to clamp01(m)
    Set out.y to clamp01(y)
    Set out.k to clamp01(k)
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RGB FLOAT CHANNELS -> CMYK
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "rgb_to_cmyk" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns CMYK:
    @Reasoning
    Convert linear RGB Float channels (unit-interval) to CMYK using the
    standard subtractive transform:
        K = 1 - max(R, G, B)
        if K = 1: all C/M/Y = 0
        else:
            C = (1 - R - K) / (1 - K)
            M = (1 - G - K) / (1 - K)
            Y = (1 - B - K) / (1 - K)
    The formula is exact for the simple subtractive model and is the
    starting point for any ICC-profile-driven conversion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Six multiplies / subtracts plus one divide; pure black short-circuits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant cost. ~15 FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r_c be clamp01(r)
    Let g_c be clamp01(g)
    Let b_c be clamp01(b)
    Let max_c be max3(r_c, g_c, b_c)
    Let k_val be 1.0 minus max_c
    Let out be a value of type CMYK
    If k_val is greater than or equal to 1.0:
        Set out.c to 0.0
        Set out.m to 0.0
        Set out.y to 0.0
        Set out.k to 1.0
        Return out
    End If
    Let denom be 1.0 minus k_val
    Set out.c to ((1.0 minus r_c) minus k_val) divided by denom
    Set out.m to ((1.0 minus g_c) minus k_val) divided by denom
    Set out.y to ((1.0 minus b_c) minus k_val) divided by denom
    Set out.k to k_val
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CMYK -> RGB FLOAT CHANNELS (via 24-byte output buffer)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CMYK_TRIPLE_SIZE as Integer is 24
Constant CMYK_TRIPLE_R_OFFSET as Integer is 0
Constant CMYK_TRIPLE_G_OFFSET as Integer is 8
Constant CMYK_TRIPLE_B_OFFSET as Integer is 16

Process called "cmyk_to_rgb" takes c as CMYK returns CMYK:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a CMYK value to its linear RGB equivalent via the inverse
    subtractive formula. Reuses the CMYK struct as a Float triple holder
    for the result (c/m/y fields receive r/g/b and k is set to 0) to
    avoid the cross-module qualified-type-in-parameter restriction of
    the bootstrap parser.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    R = (1 - C) * (1 - K); analogous for G, B. K of the output is forced
    to 0 since the result is RGB.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six multiplies / subtracts.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let one_minus_k be 1.0 minus c.k
    Let out be a value of type CMYK
    Set out.c to (1.0 minus c.c) multiplied by one_minus_k
    Set out.m to (1.0 minus c.m) multiplied by one_minus_k
    Set out.y to (1.0 minus c.y) multiplied by one_minus_k
    Set out.k to 0.0
    Return out
End Process

Process called "cmyk_to_rgb_r" takes c as CMYK returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the red channel of the CMYK -> RGB conversion as a discrete
    Float. Useful when the caller has separate code paths per channel.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (1 - C) * (1 - K).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two multiplies + two subtracts.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (1.0 minus c.c) multiplied by (1.0 minus c.k)
End Process

Process called "cmyk_to_rgb_g" takes c as CMYK returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the green channel of the CMYK -> RGB conversion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (1 - M) * (1 - K).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two multiplies + two subtracts.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (1.0 minus c.m) multiplied by (1.0 minus c.k)
End Process

Process called "cmyk_to_rgb_b" takes c as CMYK returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the blue channel of the CMYK -> RGB conversion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (1 - Y) * (1 - K).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two multiplies + two subtracts.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (1.0 minus c.y) multiplied by (1.0 minus c.k)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOTAL INK COVERAGE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "cmyk_total_ink_coverage" takes c as CMYK returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Compute the Total Ink Coverage (TIC) / Total Area Coverage (TAC) of
    a CMYK colour, expressed as a fraction (0.0 .. 4.0). Production
    presses typically limit TIC to 2.40-3.20 (240%-320%) to control ink
    saturation, dot gain, and drying. Magazine printing on coated stock
    accepts 320%; newsprint sits around 240%.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sum of the four ink channels.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((c.c plus c.m) plus c.y) plus c.k
End Process

Process called "cmyk_total_ink_coverage_percent" takes c as CMYK returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Convenience form of cmyk_total_ink_coverage that returns the result
    as a percentage (0..400) matching how press operators express the
    constraint.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Multiplies the sum by 100.0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (cmyk_total_ink_coverage(c)) multiplied by 100.0
End Process

Process called "cmyk_within_ink_limit" takes c as CMYK, limit_fraction as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Predicate returning 1 when the CMYK total ink coverage is within the
    supplied fractional limit (e.g., 3.20 for 320%); 0 otherwise.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    One subtraction and one compare.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (cmyk_total_ink_coverage(c)) is greater than limit_fraction:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EQUALITY
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "cmyk_approx_equal" takes a as CMYK, b as CMYK, tolerance as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Componentwise approximate equality used by KAT tests where Float
    arithmetic introduces sub-ULP error in the inverse-RGB roundtrip.
    Returns 1 when every channel pair is within the supplied tolerance.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four absolute-difference compares; short-circuits on the first
    mismatch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four subtracts + four compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dc be a.c minus b.c
    If dc is less than 0.0:
        Set dc to 0.0 minus dc
    End If
    If dc is greater than tolerance:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dm be a.m minus b.m
    If dm is less than 0.0:
        Set dm to 0.0 minus dm
    End If
    If dm is greater than tolerance:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dy be a.y minus b.y
    If dy is less than 0.0:
        Set dy to 0.0 minus dy
    End If
    If dy is greater than tolerance:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dk be a.k minus b.k
    If dk is less than 0.0:
        Set dk to 0.0 minus dk
    End If
    If dk is greater than tolerance:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
